'''Blanford's bridle snake''' (''Lycodon davisonii'') <ref name=NRDB/><ref name="EDR"/> is a [[species]] of harmless [[Colubridae|colubrid]] [[snake]] [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Asia]].<ref name="UBIO" /><ref name=NRDB /> Blanford's bridle snake is so named because its slim body resembles the bridle used to control horses.

==Geographic range==
''L. davisonii'' is found in [[Cambodia]], [[China]], [[Laos]], [[Myanmar]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Thailand]].<ref name=IUCN />

==Etymology==
The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]], ''davisonii'', is in honor of [[British people|British]] [[Ornithology|ornithologist]] [[William Ruxton Davison]].<ref name="EDR">Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. xiii + 296 pp. {{ISBN|978-1-4214-0135-5}}. (''Dryocalamus davisonii'', p. 66).</ref>

